<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0097</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0097</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Dr Ruth Boyask, Plymouth University</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ffectiveness of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">cademisation in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">arrowing the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ap for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">isadvantaged </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">hildren</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Evidence from the BELMAS Structural Reform Research Programme funded study:</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">‘New Relations between Local Authorities and Schools’</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academisation has changed the responsibilities and functions of local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (LAs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in resp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ect of their work with schools, yet they retain significant statutory responsibility for fair access to schooling, the needs of vulnerable children, school improvement and performance, and advocacy for parents, families and children. Their ability to act u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pon these responsibilities is affected by financial loss as schools convert to academies and central government cuts funding. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The resultant climate is competitive, and in some cases, combative.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This paper reports on findings of case studies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> four </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hin one region. Three of the authorities attempted to mitigate competition within the market-led environment, whereas one embraced it. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The findings from the project of relevance to this project are divided into two themes: 1) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Statutory responsibilities of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> LAs and reduced financial resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and 2) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Confusion in functions and responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of LAs.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Statutory responsibilities of LAs and reduced financial resources </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Even though academisation promotes school autonomy, LAs remain statutorily responsible for s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ome of the operations of academies, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(for example,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">statutory assessment of SEN and the prosecution of non-attendees at school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. While responsibilities for vulnerable children and many other serious concerns and issues come to the local authority, limited fi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nancial and human resources can cause significant oversights. A core </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">function for the LA is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the capacity to act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on all concerns and issues that are brought to it by stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Confusion in functions and responsibilities of LAs</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Respondents from the four case studies all reported some element of confusion in respect of their responsibilities to schools. There are responsibilities enshrined in the statutes themselves that have not changed, against which Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inspect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> local authori</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ties, yet different messages </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">about school autonomy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emerge from the Department for Education. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These ambiguities are exacerbated when schools are transitioning to academy status, and also impact upon an LA’s capacity to offer a stable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">set of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s for cru</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cial functions like school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This research suggests that a market economy of schooling and services to schools impacts upon local authorities’ capacity to meet the needs of disadvantaged children and young people. LAs need the financ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ial and human resources to respond to the issues that come to them. As inequalities within society increase, there will be greater demand placed upon LAs to respond to the needs of children.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a lack of clarity around role and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> responsibility in the interactions betwee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n schools and local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">external relationships</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> While a simple solution to the ambiguit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> may appear to be more clearly defining lines of accountability, I think there is a deeper problem </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be resolved. Current policies impacting upon the education and care of children emphasise competition, including the academies programme, forcing school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s and LAs to compete for custom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> against co-operati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or community engagement. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">An overview </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The expansion of the academies programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">since 2010 has resulted in a profound reconfiguration of the responsibilities and functions of local authorities in respect of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">schools. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Academies Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (2010)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Schools White Paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (2010) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">governing and management bodies of academies have new responsibilities that previously had been responsib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ilities within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> local authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">greater school-level control over finances and expenditure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Yet Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (LAs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> still retain important responsibilities in respect of schooling including:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ensuring there is fair access to schooling</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Supporting vulnerable children</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Improving the performance of schools and ensuring high standards  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Using their de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mocratic mandate to advocate for parents, families and children </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(DfE, 2010; Parish, Baxter and Sandals, 2012). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The capacity of LAs to enact these responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> affected by significant funding cuts to their formula grants (Stabe &amp; Jones, 2011), but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also financial loss as schools convert to academies. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cademisation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has resulted in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">found</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s recognise and enact responsibilities for disadvantaged children in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">schools, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes in financing have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> also affected how local authori</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ties relate to maintained schools. Furthermo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re, the promotion of autonomous</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s has created a competitive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">environment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that works against the best interests of disadvantaged children, making the job of the local authority to ensure the needs of the most</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> vulnerable are met much more difficult. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An LA Senior Manager</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with strategic responsibility for services to schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">claimed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">within her LA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where 44% of schools are academies, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relationships between schools had become “combative”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a result of competition.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have trialled different solutions to changes in their resource, but within four </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">case studies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of LAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> each had made immense moves away from statutory provision as a norm. Of the four </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> only one fully embr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aced a competitive market model to achieve its statutory responsibility to the social good, whereas the other local authorities have differently attempted to mitigate the challenges of a competitive environment so they may enact this responsibility. This h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as been through the following mechanisms:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Holding onto a limited statutory provision (although in light of recent funding cuts this is unlikely to continue)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Community and stakeholder engagement;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Utilising business structures founded on principles of coope</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ration and mutuality.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.1 Evidential basis of the report</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">draws upon findings from the ‘New Relations between Local Authorities and Schools’ study to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">present evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that addresses the terms of reference of this select committee inquiry in respect of the functions and responsibilities of local authorities. The report presents findings </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from this study </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">addresses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he functions and responsibilities in relation to acad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emies and free schools of local authorities operating between the Secretary o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f State and individual schools, and considers the significance of these findings for determining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">what these functions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and responsibilities should be. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The study has focused upon four </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from within a single region looking at how their relationships with schools have changed as a result of structural reform in the schooling sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Table</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. Case Studies: The Local Authorities</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:115.5pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local Authority 1</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-st